{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "From this latent feature matrix, we can then learn a conditional distribution from each row, which models the positions or velocities of the corresponding player.",
    "To do this, we extend the backbone encoder with conditional variational autoencoder (CVAE 28, 29).",
    "Specifically, for the u-th row of H id, h u, we first map its latent embedding to the parameters of a twodimensional Gaussian distribution N ðμ u jσ u Þ, and then sample the coordinates and velocities from this distribution.",
    "At training time, we can efficiently propagate gradients through this sampling operation using the reparameterisation trick 28: sample a random value ϵ u ∼ N ð0,1Þ for each player from the unit Gaussian distribution, and then treat μ u + σ u ϵ u as the sample for this player.",
    "In what follows, we omit edge features for brevity."
  ],
